  "prompt": "Why do people with white skin get burnt easily?",
  "response": "People with white skin tend to get sunburned more easily because their skin produces less melanin compared to individuals with darker skin tones. Melanin is the pigment responsible for skin, hair, and eye color, and it provides some natural protection against the harmful effects of ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun. Here are the key reasons why those with white skin are more prone to sunburn:\n\n1. **Lower Melanin Levels**: White skin has less melanin, which means there is less natural protection against UV rays. Melanin absorbs and dissipates UV radiation, reducing its ability to damage skin cells.\n\n2. **Less Effective DNA Repair**: UV radiation can damage DNA in skin cells, potentially leading to mutations that cause skin cancer. People with darker skin have melanin that not only blocks more UV radiation but also helps repair DNA damage more effectively.\n\n3. **Skin Type and Sensitivity**: Individuals with white skin often have a lighter skin type (e.g., Fitzpatrick skin type I or II), which is more sensitive to UV exposure and burns more quickly.\n\n4. **Cultural and Behavioral Factors**: People with white skin may also spend more time in the sun, especially in regions where they are not accustomed to high UV levels, increasing their risk of sunburn.\n\nTo protect against sunburn, people with white skin are advised to use broad-spectrum sunscreen, wear protective clothing, and limit sun exposure during peak UV hours (10 a.m. to 4 p.m.). Regular skin checks and early detection of any changes are also important for preventing long-term damage, including skin cancer.",
